For a function
```csharp
public string[] BetweenBrackets(string[] l) {
  if (l is ["(", .. var between, ")"])
    return between;
  return null;
}
```
The lowered code is
```csharp
public string[] BetweenBrackets(string[] l) {
  if (l != null)  {
    int num = l.Length;
    if (num >= 2 && l[0] == "(") {
      string[] subArray = RuntimeHelpers.GetSubArray(l, new Range(new Index(1), new Index(1, true)));
      if (l[num - 1] == ")") {
        return subArray;
      }
    }
  }
  return null;
}
```
As you can see, the array for the `between` variable gets created before the pattern gets fully matched.
This means that for input like `( hello world`, this function will still allocate the array even though it is completely unnecessary.

**Expected Behavior**:
The value of a variable storing the result of a slice pattern should be created once the pattern is fully matched, to avoid unnecessary allocations.
**Actual Behavior**:
The variable gets created before the pattern gets fully matched.

